Global and Regional Analysis of Dental School Nutrition Education Survey

Executive Summary

This analysis examines nutrition education practices across 56 dental schools worldwide after removing ADEMA duplicate entries (“adema” and “ADEMA”). There are significant global patterns and regional variations in integration methods, teaching approaches, research activities, and collaboration interests.

Global Overview: - Total Institutions: 56 schools worldwide - Regional Distribution: Europe (45%), North America (25%), Other Regions (30%) - Data Quality: Duplicate entries removed, comprehensive coverage across 3 major regions

Key Findings by Region

Regional Characteristics Analysis

North America (14 schools, 25%)

Strengths: - Strong research infrastructure (50% conduct research) - High integration rates - Consistent program structure - Well-established curricula

Challenges: - Time constraints remain primary barrier - Need for enhanced clinical integration

Europe (25 schools, 44.6%)

Strengths: - Highest collaboration interest (91.7%) - Systematic curriculum approaches - Strong clinical integration focus - Years 2-3 concentration strategy

Challenges: - Variable hour allocation (wide range) - Time constraint barriers - Some schools not including nutrition

Other Regions (17 schools, 30.4%)

Strengths: - Growing engagement and motivation - Flexible curriculum approaches - Strong improvement focus - Balanced academic year distribution

Challenges: - Lower research engagement - Resource limitations - Faculty expertise development needs

Conclusions and Recommendations

The regional analysis of 56 dental schools (after duplicate removal) reveals:

  1. Global Integration Trend: Most schools (61.8%) use integrated approaches across regions
  2. Regional Specialization: Each region shows distinct strengths and approaches
  3. Universal Challenges: Time constraints are the primary barrier across all regions (>80%)
  4. Collaboration Opportunity: High interest globally (89.1%) for multi-institutional partnerships
  5. Research Variation: North America leads in research activity, opportunities for collaboration

Strategic Recommendations:

For Global Collaboration: - Create resource-sharing platforms to address time constraints - Establish mentorship programs between established and developing regions - Focus on prosthodontics integration as identified workshop priority

For Curriculum Development: - Standardise core competencies while allowing regional adaptation - Develop specialty-specific modules (particularly prosthodontics) - Create assessment tools that work across different systems - Implement evidence-based integration strategies
